<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Standard letter</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the British Retail Consortium</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.55pt; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></h1><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.9pt; text-indent:-28.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The British Retail Consortium (BRC) is the leading voice of the retail sector, representing small and independent stores through to the large multiples, selling food and non-food products and services, and operating on the High Street, out of town, in community and rural shops and online.</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.9pt; text-indent:-28.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Our members will be responsible for implementing any mandatory charge for single use carrier bags in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">.  They will also be instrumental in explaining the charge to their customers.  We have worked closely with the other UK Governments on the development and introduction of their carrier bag levies and believe that any charge in England should be clear, straight forward and consistent with the approaches taken in Wales, Northern Ireland and Scotland. </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.55pt; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></h1><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.9pt; text-indent:-28.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">This submission focuses on the following key points </span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The rationale behind the proposals for a charge in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is unclear.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that the proposed charge for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is not consistent with the charge in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the charge is introduced as currently proposed, retailers will be faced with complex messages to communicate to shoppers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BRC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that the proposed charge should be applied to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">single use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carrier bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A focus on plastic bags only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could have the unintended consequence of acting as an incentive to some retailers to offer paper bags, with a higher environmental impact, instead of single use plastic bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodegradable bags sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be seen as a substitute for single use plastic bags and should not be given away for free</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any carrier bag charge should apply to all retailers regardless of size.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.55pt; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction and b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ackground</span></h1><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Single use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">plastic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> carrier bags were introduced as an efficient and inexpensive aid to shopping by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> retailers in the 1980s.  With a small number of exceptions, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">these bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">became the required norm across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> supermarket industry by the early 1990s.</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">In 2012, around 8.1 billion single-use bags were used by supermarket customers in the UK –a decrease of 34% compared with 2006, when 12.2 billionsingle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> use carrier bags were distributed by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">supermarkets</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">.  Over the same period, there has been a 51% reduction in the amount of new plastic used in all carrier bags.</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Our members led the way in providing bags for life and in providing facilities for our customers to recycle single use plastic bags, with millions recycled every year. Data published by WRAP in July 2013 shows </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">60</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> of stores have front-of-store recycling points offering customers convenient ways to recycle bags and packaging whenever they do their food shopping.  This is also becoming the norm for supermarket shopping online, where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">customers are offered loyalty points for choosing to have their items delivered without bags, and delivery drivers collect and recycle bags after use.</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Single use polythene </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">carrier bags account for less than 1% of household waste</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, however, they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">are seen by some as a symbol of a throw-away culture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> and receive a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">disproportionate amount of attention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> in comparison to their minor impact on the environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> Unfortunately, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">he issue acts as a distraction from the more important and more challenging issues of radically reducing waste and carbon emissions to meet stretching 2020 goals.  </span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">While t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">he retail sector in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">has successfully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> supported efforts to reduce carrier bag use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> working hard on a wide range of far more significant environmental projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> which will make a much bigger difference to the environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The BRC believes that Government’s and retailers’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">efforts would be better focused on areas of higher environmental impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, such as reducing food waste.</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">We recognise that if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> sees reducing the use of carrier bags as a priority, it will have to go beyond voluntary measures.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">our members operate at a national level across the four UK nations and</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">we believe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">it is crucial for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">any new legislation to be as consistent as possible with that in place or proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> for the other UK nations.  </span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">We are concerned that the proposed charge for England is not consistent with the charge in Wales, Northern Ireland or Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the Government’s explicit commitment to ‘Better Regulation’ and reducing unnecessary business costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The proposed charging regime is not logical and, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">f </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Defra does introduce a charge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, retailers will be faced with complex messages to communicate to shoppers as to why some shops and some non-reusable bags are exempt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> from the charge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> and why these exemptions do not exist elsewhere in the UK.</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.55pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The environmental impacts of the proposed 5p charge in England</span></h1><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The rationale behind the proposals for a charge in England is unclear.  A focus on plastic bags suggests that the proposals have been drawn up with marine plastic waste and wildlife in mind.  However, the Defra press release also refers to the environment and litter (albeit more indirectly), but non-plastic carrier bags and biodegradable bags have a higher carbon footprint, and are just as likely to become litter as plastic carrier bags.  Furthermore, many stores will continue to distribute plastic carrier bags free of charge if organisations employing 250 people or fewer are exempt from the requirement to charge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">undermining all three stated objectives of the charge, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">creating unnecessary costs for business and confusion for customers.</span></h2><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.9pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">A focus on single use plastic bags only</span></h2><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The BRC believes that the proposed charge should apply to all single use carrier bags regardless of material type (subject to a number of specific exemptions as applied in Wales and Northern Ireland – including hot food to go, on the grounds of food safety).  A charge for all single use carrier bags would ensure a consistent approach across the UK nations and would send a clear message to shoppers that there will be a minimum charge for single use bags and that they should bring reusable bags with them.</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Carbon footprint</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Defra’s proposed approach appears to ignore evidence from an Environment Agency study</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, published in 2011, which found that single use carrier bags made from high-density polyethylene have the lowest carbon footprint of any type of bag.  A paper bag has to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">used at least three times to have less environmental impact than a single use plastic bag.  See figure 1 below.</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Figure 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">: The amount of prima</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ry use required to take </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">bags below the global warming potential of single use carrier bags </span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:35.45pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:177.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Type of carrier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">bag</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:134.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Number of uses required have less environmental impact than a single use plastic bag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">used once and thrown away</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:106.3pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Number of uses required have less environmental impact than a single use plastic bag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> used 3 times</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:177.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Paper bag </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:134.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3 </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:106.3pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:177.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">LDPE bag </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(low cost reusable carrier bag)</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:134.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4 </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:106.3pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">12</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:177.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Non-woven PP bag </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(heavy, more durable reusable carrier bag, often with stiffening inserts made from non-woven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olypropylene)</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:134.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11 </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:106.3pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">33</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:14.75pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:177.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cotton bag </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:134.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">131 </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:106.3pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">393</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The same report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">state</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> that whilst paper carrier bags are from renewable sources and are biodegradable, compostable and recyclable, they require significantly more energy to manufacture and transport than plastic bags and normally have limited reusability. If disposed of in landfill, they are likely to degrade and release methane</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Mixed messages for consumers</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We are concerned that a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> focus on restricting the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">use of single use plastic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> will send a policy signal to consumers that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">single use bags made from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">paper (and other materials) are environmentally acceptable and can continue to be used and disposed of in unlimited quantities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This would be short-sighted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> given the greater environmental impact of paper carrier bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> This is also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">potentially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the case with the proposed exemption </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">biodegradable polythene bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> which meet a specified standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Unintended consequences</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">If the charge is not applied to all single use carrier bags, it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">prompt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">some retailers to avoid being placed at a competitive disadvantage by offering paper bags, with a higher environmental impact, instead of single use plastic bags.  This would increase the environmental impact of single use bags which runs contrary to the aims of the proposed charge.   </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A charge for single use plastic bags only was adopted in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Republic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> (RoI) in 2002.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">At least two </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of our members, operating across the UK and in the R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">oI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, report that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">felt compelled by customer responses to offer levy-exempt paper bags following the introduction of the charge in R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">I.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">One of these retailers offers paper bags for food purchases only and uses a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">much reduced volume of single use plastic bags for non-food purchases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in ROI.  However, the switch to paper bags for food purchases has effectively </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">increas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the carbon footprint of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">this retailer’s carrier bags in ROI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">by 300</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Should a larger retailer adopt ‘free’ paper carrier bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the whole sector maybe compelled to follow (as happened with free </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">plastic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">carrier bags in the 1980s).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  The majority of our members believe that the hot food-to-go retail sector should be exempt from the charge on the grounds of food safety. However, if the sector is included in the final regulations, it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">also possible that those food-to-go retailers currently using single use carrier bags would consider switching to paper bags in order to create a level playing field with other food to go retailers, many of whom currently offer paper bags and would not be compelled to charge for those bags.  </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.9pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Proposed exemption for biodegradable bags</span></h2><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">While we agree that there may be benefits to arriving at an agreed national standard for biodegradable bags, we do not believe that they should be seen as a substitute for single use plastic bags and should not be given away for free.</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We understand that biodegradable bags produced to any agreed national standard would not be available in time for the introduction of the proposed charge in autumn 2015.  This again could cause confusion to customers if certain biodegradable bags are exempted from the charge once the charge has been in operation for some time.  O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ur members would benefit from a clear definition on what the criteria exemption would be as soon as possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">It is que</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">stionable whether a move to bio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">degradable carrier bags in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> would develop the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">K</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> bio-degradable bag industry.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In the absence of large scale </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> polythene carrier bag manufacturers, the majority of carrier bags are produced overseas.  A move to bio-degradable bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is likely to change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the specification given by retailers to their existing carrier bag suppliers, rather than creating/developing a new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> industry.</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There is a c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">onflict between bio-degradable bags and the re-use message. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">To date, BRC member voluntary actions and the legislation in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">/ NI/ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> have f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ocussed on reducing usage.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Bio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">degradability addresses different impacts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">- those of litter and mari</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ne pollution, and a move to bio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">degradable bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> as a substitution for single use plastic bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> will muddy the water and lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">se the focus on reducing usage.  </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This begs the question, does the Government want customers to use lots of biodegradable bags and grow a new industry in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, or does it want customers to learn to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">re-use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">over and over again and store for later use?  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Bio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">degradable bags can be really confusing for the consumer and very challenging for the retailer to be able to communicate how to dispose with these bags correctly. Biodegradable bags cannot </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">recycled along with single use carrier bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">– a challenge for those supermarkets providing front of store carrier bag recycling points. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> While Defra is aware of this, and is working with bag manufacturers and reprocessors to explore whether a biodegradable bags can be developed that is compatible with current recycling arrangements for single use plastic bags and film, this is another hurdle than would need to be overcome if certain biodegradable bags were exempt from the charge.   </span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">One of our members sells </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">compostable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bio-degradable carrier bags but these are sold to be used as food waste caddy liners (i.e. they have 2 uses).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">member would expect its bio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">degradable carrier bags to only have a lower environmental impact than the combined functions of a carrier bag and a food waste caddy liner, which is more achievable. These bags are sold in areas where the local authority will accept them for food waste collection.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> They are labelled carefully and clearly take into account the needs of the customer and the local authority collection crew.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  We would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">suggest that this model should be explored by Defra but would recommend that these bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">sold at, or above, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">prevailing charge for single-use carrier bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.9pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Proposed exemption for s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">mall businesses with fewer than 250 employees</span></h2><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We would suggest that any carrier bag charge applies to all retailers.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">exemption for companies employing up to 250 people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is not logical and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">will further confuse consumers with some smaller supermarkets having to charge and other being able to provide free polythene bags.</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We are also concerned that this proposal will mean that franchise operations, such as those found in a number of food to go and convenience store chains will be exempt from the requirement to charge.  This will mean that high street retailers will not be operating on a level playing field and that some stores within the same umbrella group will be required to charge for bags while other will not.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">confusing for customers and places some retailers at a competitive disadvantage based solely on their business model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">One of our trade association members, which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">has both chains and ind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ependent retailers as members, is of the view </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">that if the charge is introduced it should be applied to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> retailers regardless of size as happens in the rest of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.55pt; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ags for life</span></h1><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Data provided by supermarkets to WRAP on carrier bag usage in 2012 shows that there was a substantial increase in the numbers and weight of bags for life purchased in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, following the introduction of a charge for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">single use carrier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">bags in October 2011.  However, in terms of weight, the increase in bags for life purchased was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">negated the reduction in weight of single use bags by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">approximately 30% of the reduction in weight of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">single use plastic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">bags, which is in addition to the typical increased plastic use due to the uplift in heavier gauge bin liner purchases.</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">An increase in the sale of all types of bags for life is to be expected following the introduction of a charge.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">e do not believe reusable bags should be subject to a charge in the future.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> Reusable bags are a valuable tool both in engaging customers in positive behaviour change and in helping them to reduce overall bag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">A reusable bag </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">charge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">will penalise customers for doing the right thing and being environmentally conscious.  Re-using bags is a totemic environmental behaviour and the extension of this principle to other areas would make a big difference in sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">consumption.</span></h2><h3 style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.55pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">essons to be learnt from other countries’ experiences </span></h1><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The experience of our members in implementing a carrier bag charge in the other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> nations and the ROI i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">s that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> irrespective of the impact being targeted, the most effective means of reducing the environmental footprint of carrier bags is to:</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Reduce the consumption of all single use bags by encouraging consumer behaviour change in the form of re-use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Communicate and support the message of re-use i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">n a clear and consistent manner;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Apply the charge consistently across retailers enabling a clear message to customers;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Ensure total transparency that charges collected from actions to restrain consumption are donated to good causes.</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">11 December 2013</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">From carrier bag monitoring data provided by supermarkets and collated by WRAP: </span><a href="http://www.wrap.org.uk/content/wrap-publishes-new-figures-carrier-bag-use"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.wrap.org.uk/content/wrap-publishes-new-figures-carrier-bag-use</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.wrap.org.uk/content/carrier-bags-reducing-their-use"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.wrap.org.uk/content/carrier-bags-reducing-their-use</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Life cycle assessment of supermarket carrier bags: a review of the bags available in 2006 – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">The Environment agency, February 2011 (</span><a href="http://a0768b4a8a31e106d8b0-50dc802554eb38a24458b98ff72d550b.r19.cf3.rackcdn.com/scho0711buan-e-e.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://a0768b4a8a31e106d8b0-50dc802554eb38a24458b98ff72d550b.r19.cf3.rackcdn.com/scho0711buan-e-e.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">)</span></p></body></html>